<TITLE>Made in India review an emotionally charged mix of politics and parenthood</TITLE>
<TEXT>
A Eva Gina Isaac newly arrived from the UK has high hopes a high level job in advertising and a strong determination to do things her way following years of failed IVF treatments Doctor Gupta Syreeta Kumar is cool competent and in charge of a clinic so in demand from foreign clients that she is now investing in an ambitious expansion programme to meet their needs Aditi Ulrika Krishnamurti the intended surrogate will earn more in nine months than she could through 10 years work in her village A dramatically potent situation is given added impetus and conceptual complexity when politics disrupt the personal agendas State elections loom a ban is introduced on foreigners paying for surrogacy in India What follows is a revelation of the women s characters under pressure brilliantly multifaceted performances from Isaac Kumar and Krishnamurti which exposes questions surrounding surrogacy without offering glib answers and wider economic issues a politician s voiceover attacks the ban claiming surrogacy allows produce of India to make wealth flow back to the country as well as semi submerged postcolonial attitudes Places are precisely evoked and yet also flow and twine thanks to the combined effects of Prema Mehta s lighting Arun Ghosh s sound design also original music and Denno s multiple screens on to which are projected Shanaz Gulzar s video images Each element enhances the play s competing tensions between fragmentation and cohesion opposites tautly balanced by Katie Posner s fine direction The whole makes for an intellectually and emotionally stirring encounter 
</TEXT>
